summary: ————————————————————— Voicemail #17 To: Tony Stark From: Peter Parker Hey, Mr. Stark! I, um- I got your voicemail. I’m really,...
body:
—————————————————————

Voicemail #17

To: Tony Stark

From: Peter Parker

Hey, Mr. Stark! I, um- I got your voicemail. I’m really, really glad to hear that you still want to hear from me. That’s, like, super awesome ‘cause I kinda enjoy leaving these reports.

So, uh, this week. What happened? Let me think…

Oh, I ran out of web fluid yesterday for the first time in a while. I had made a pretty big supply earlier so I hadn’t done the whole ‘don’t let the chem teacher see you stir some weird mixture inside the lab drawer’ thing recently. Anyway, I wasn’t paying much attention when I was doing it because the teacher was going over the answers to the chem test, and Flash was talking to Michelle all smiley and stuff in the corner of my eye, and Ned was texting me about how hard the gov test was, and I must have just gotten real distracted. Because one moment I’m stirring my web fluid slowly and another moment it’s completely overflowing out of the beaker. I panicked because, one, I will so totally be screwed if people see spider-webs coming out of my drawer and, two, because it’s super sticky. Like, sticky enough to mostly hold an entire boat together type of sticky.  So I shut the drawer really fast but, as I did this, the fluid splashed a little and it landed on the bottom of my pants. Of course, being the brilliant person I am, I decided to try and brush off the web fluid before anyone could see it.

But instead, my hand got stuck. To the bottom. Of my pants.

And right as I was on the floor processing the absolutely horrific mess I was in, the teacher called on me to answer some stupid electron configuration problem. So I popped up with my leg balanced against the other like I’m a flamingo and tried to make it look like resting my hand on my pants is a totally normal thing to do. I answered the question with a way-too-big smile that was mostly used to distract the 30 other students looking at me. And once the teacher had turned back around, I ran through all the possible ways I could get out of this situation.

One, I could just rip my pants and get my hand free. It seemed like a pretty good idea, except I was 99% sure that it would make a loud noise that causes everyone to look at me and the ripped part of pant and spider-web concoction stuck to my hand. So that was out.

Two, I could cut my pants. But my scissors were in my backpack on the other side of the room and I could already picture myself falling all over the place if I were to hop over there and get it.

Three, I could text Ned. Ask him to cause some sort of distraction that would allow me to rip my hand free, jump away to my locker, and change into my extra gym shorts.

That plan seemed solid, so I texted Ned with a message that said “Hey, man. I got my hand stuck to my pants with web fluid. I need you to cause some sort of distraction so I can get my hand free without anyone noticing”. As I wrote the text, it seemed like a lot to ask, so I added one of those smiley face emojis before I sent it.

Less than a minute of awkwardly standing at the lab table had passed before I heard yelling from the halls.

I didn’t really process what was happening before, bam, Ned bursts through the door screaming, “THERE’S A HUGE CAR CRASH OUTSIDE!”

The chem teacher looked at him mildly concerned and majorly confused while my classmates paid almost no attention.

Ned, hesitated, then yelled, “…and, um, IRON MAN IS FLYING AROUND OUTSIDE ABOVE IT!”

At once, all the students leapt out of their seat and flocked to the window because I guess that’s the effect you have on people, Mr. Stark. With the amount of noise everyone was making, I ripped my hand off of my pants without anyone noticing. I gave Ned a high-five, sprinted down the hallway, changed out of my ripped pants, and sprinted back into class before anyone even knew I was missing. I even had time to shove the web fluid into my backpack, because the class was so preoccupied with trying to get a glimpse of you.

So, in the end, everything turned out pretty good. I’ll send you more voicemails later, okay, Mr. Stark? Oh, and if anyone asks about yesterday, you were totally flying around around in Queens.

—————————————————————

blog.description: Most of the comics I read are Marvels from 1984. Every time I read a comic, I post a comment. That's pretty much it.

title: A Cry of Beasts
body:
Iron Man #160

Another solid entry from the new writer.

  • What Do the Villains Want? Sabotage. And theft. And Iron Man is in the way.
  • Works really well, as a heist thriller. Terse, urgent dialogue, etc.
  • Tony’s date for the evening is an actress. Her alcoholism is overstated, yes, but it serves to underscore the ongoing tension in Tony’s life.
  • Denny O'Neil (2 of 49). 

8/10
